      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was performed across three refinement levels (coarse, medium, fine) for both the screw and the UHMWPE block. The Richardson extrapolation-based Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for stiffness QoI was 0.8%, well below the 5% threshold. Final mesh density selected at medium refinement to balance accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver residuals were monitored and confirmed to converge below 1e-6 for all load steps. No divergence or spurious oscillations were observed across the 11 simulation instances. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds the required Gradation 1 for this factor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Model setup procedures are documented in a controlled simulation protocol. Independent peer review of boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and load application was conducted by a second qualified analyst. No use errors were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic constitutive models are appropriate for the titanium alloy screw under the sub-yield loading regime of ASTM F1717. The UHMWPE block is modeled with a bilinear isotropic hardening formulation validated against coupon-level test data. Model form assumptions are documented and justified relative to the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, yield 880 MPa; UHMWPE: E=1.0 GPa) were sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing performed at an ISO 17025-accredited laboratory. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of production screws. Uncertainty in inputs was propagated via Latin hypercube sampling (n=200) confirming QoI sensitivity within bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Eleven (N=11) non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from production lots were tested across two independent laboratories. Sample selection followed a stratified protocol to capture expected dimensional variation. Sample size satisfies the ASME V&V 40 recommendation for medium model risk with medium decision consequence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level. Note: this factor does not meet the required level; a supplementary analytical argument is provided in the decision rationale.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single environmental condition (23°C, ambient humidity) per ASTM F1717 protocol. The required level of 2 demands at least two distinct test condition variations (e.g., temperature or rate). Only a single test condition was employed, yielding an achieved level of 1. This shortfall is acknowledged and addressed in the overall decision rationale through analytical sensitivity analysis demonstrating negligible temperature dependence of titanium alloy stiffness over the physiological range."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions were set to match the experimental fixture geometry, grip engagement length, and applied displacement rate. A one-to-one mapping table between experimental parameters and simulation inputs was reviewed and approved by both the modeling team and the test laboratory principal investigator."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the validation metric E/uval per ASME V&V 20. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) returned E/uval < 1.96, and percent differences were below the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias across the N=11 sample."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Qualitative confirmation that selected QoIs are directly traceable to the clinical and regulatory decision context.",
      "rationale": "The three selected quantities of interest — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the primary performance endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly cited in the FDA guidance document for spinal implant 510(k) submissions. Each QoI maps unambiguously to a clinical failure mode: stiffness governs load-sharing with the bone graft, yield force governs permanent deformation risk, and force at 40 mm displacement governs catastrophic failure risk. A qualitative assessment by the clinical affairs team confirmed that no additional QoIs are required to characterize the construct's biomechanical acceptability for the intended COU. The relevance of these QoIs was reviewed and endorsed by an independent orthopedic surgeon consultant with spinal instrumentation expertise. This factor was evaluated through structured expert elicitation and documentary traceability review rather than a graduated quantitative rubric, reflecting the inherently qualitative nature of clinical relevance judgments at the current state of practice."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 compression-bending bench test) directly replicates the loading scenario and construct configuration of the intended COU. The test fixture, load application point, and construct geometry are identical to those used in the regulatory submission. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the intended use."
    }
